frameDefinitions: An State_of_affairs will come to hold with respect to a Protagonist at some future time.
While in motion, an Impactor makes sudden, forcible contact with the Impactee, or two Impactors both move, mutually making forcible contact.
Words in this frame have to do with a Cognizer adding some Phenomenon to their model of the world.
Some phenomenon (the Stimulus) provokes a particular emotion in an Experiencer.
An Agent causes an Impactor to make sudden, forcible contact with an Impactee, or manipulates two (or more) Impactors so that they make mutual forcible contact.

A Phenomenon (an external or cognitive event or situation) comes into the awareness of an Experiencer, resulting in a perceptually punctual change in the Experiencer's conception of the Phenomenon or entities and facts associated with it.

The <fen>Cognizer</fen> is the person who becomes aware of a <fen>Phenomenon</fen>. It is normally expressed as an External Argument.

<fen>Topic</fen> indicates the general field within which the <fen>Phenomenon</fen> is found.

This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Cognizer</fen> becomes aware of the <fen>Phenomenon</fen>.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> reacts emotionally or psychologically to the <fen>Stimulus</fen>.
The <fen>Stimulus</fen> is the event or entity which brings about the emotional or psychological state of the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.

The <fen>Impactee</fen> is the entity which is hit by the <fen>Impactor</fen>.

The <fen>Impactors</fen> are the multiple entities that collide.
The <fen>Agent</fen>  causes an impact.

The <fen>Cause</fen> marks expressions that indicate some non-intentional, 
typically non-human, force that causes an <fen>Impactor</fen> to make sudden, 
forcible contact with an Impactee.

The <fen>Phenomenon</fen> is the entity that evokes a cognitive reaction for the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> in the entity who experiences the cognitive impact brought about by the <fen>Phenomenon</fen>.
